00:01:18.120 --> 00:01:20.940
Climbing Position

00:01:21.640 --> 00:01:25.020
Okay, so the first step is to establish position
in the climb up

00:01:25.030 --> 00:01:30.590
So, we're gonna use the rail that's mounted
to a wall to eliminate any intensities of

00:01:30.590 --> 00:01:32.860
grip or just general strength

00:01:32.860 --> 00:01:37.700
He is gonna walk his feet up the wall until
they are about even with his hips

00:01:38.280 --> 00:01:41.400
He's gonna drop his non power leg down

00:01:41.409 --> 00:01:43.680
And I'm gonna pull his foot of the wall

00:01:43.680 --> 00:01:47.810
So, this is a less balance position, cause
is only one foot place on the wall

00:01:47.810 --> 00:01:51.010
So I'm gonna make in the make sure he has
contact with the wall

00:01:51.010 --> 00:01:53.000
there is no really any weight on there

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.799
So its top knee its gonna be turn out

00:01:55.799 --> 00:01:58.799
You notice that his hips gets closer to the
wall

00:01:58.799 --> 00:02:03.339
Its really important to have good hip mobility
to get into an optimal position of pull

00:02:03.840 --> 00:02:07.560
And finally his foot is gonna be placed flat
against the wall

00:02:07.570 --> 00:02:10.299
to allow to roll up when he pulls

00:02:10.299 --> 00:02:13.539
His arms are kept long to mimic the bottom
position of the climb up

00:02:13.540 --> 00:02:15.279
to initiate the pull

